segments.text: Oh, my goodness.
Yeah.
Let's see.
Did your wife begin teaching then?
She taught the next fall, fall of 1956.
She taught the second grade for seven years and then moved up to high school.
She was real fortunate.
She had her degree in French and Spanish
And, of course, taught the second grade.
She went to LSU one semester to take elementary because it looks like she was going to teach in Baton Rouge, and she needed a teacher's certificate in Louisiana.
And then we came on back, and so fortunately, that's what happened.
All right, back to your teaching.
Did you feel that the electrical engineering department
have provided the facilities, the laboratory equipment that were appropriate when you got here?
For what we were doing then, yeah.
You had two machinery labs, and on the third floor you had electronics.
The second floor they had that IBM 650, which they put in there.
They also had a network analyzer, a network calculator, which was furnished by the utilities.
And this is how they run their transmission problems on there.
And so this was about it.
And of course, there's only one PhD in the whole department then.
And that was a hallmark.
None of the rest of them had PhDs.
Ed Andrews
came back from, he had his, Ed Andrew was the first one to walk across the strage in G. Wally White.
And he got his Ph.D., and Andrew was the first one.
I'd like to have gotten a picture of that last one to go across and let her have a picture of him.
Can you help me understand in the 30-some-odd years you've taught,
how the program changed in electrical engineering.
Well, they're unrecognizable now, of course.
John Paul German, of course, he came here to teach field theory and this sort of thing, and so the real explosion came with the integrated circuit, with the transistor and this sort of thing.
When was that?
Of course, the transistor discrete components were in use by then.
We didn't run any experiments except with vacuum tubes by then.
And of course, the IBM 650 had 4,000 memory storage locations.
And of course, that was the only computer on the campus.
And then of course, they built the data processing center down where they put in the 709 and this sort of thing.
But it's just unbelievable the change that occurred.
Who were the people who deserve special mention as helping to get those changes accomplished?
Are there some deans or some department heads or faculty members?
In electrical engineering?
That deserve special mention?
Recently or what?
Any time during those.
Who were the people that made the difference?
Back in those days?
Well, of course, they were all good undergraduate teachers and some graduate, but people like John, Walt Mattson, he left.
And then Mike Reckoff, he just died.
He was one of the new ones that had gone off.
A fellow named Ed Andrews, who left later, he later died.
It's really, really hard to say.
Calhoun comes as dean, and then Benson.
Oh, yeah.
How did they summarize them, describe their work as deans?
Of course, I guess Benson was the dean when I went on to the faculty, and pretty soon after that, John Calhoun came.
Well, he was dean, too.
I don't know how that works in.
I think Calhoun was first, and then he moved to the system level.
He moved on up, and then Benson became the dean.
Of course, I think the greatest thing about A&M is the strong administration.
the presidents and the deans and the department heads, everybody knew where they stood, more or less.
And of course, I think Rutter was probably the greatest of all.
Why do you think?
Because he brought us kicking and screaming into the 20th century.
He was able to keep the former students happy and the faculty happy and also the students.
to get us up into the 20th.
And here, he had just a Bachelor of Science.
Everybody scared of him.
Like he said, he said, you know, Highway 6 runs in both directions.
And one of the faculty members, they came by and resigned.
I tell people over and over, only Earl Rudder could have made those basic changes.
Then Jack Williams was a great blessing that he could build on those changes.
That if you reverse them, they both pay.
Were you aware, as a faculty member, of any specific judgments or decisions that President Rudder made or that Jack Williams made
that affected engineering?
I don't know.
I don't know of any.
I don't either.
How did you and other and your colleagues react to co-education and non-compulsory core to those changes?
Well, of course, I think we were all pretty much in favor of it.
I know my own son, he was born here, but
He had already made up his mind to go to the University of Texas, even though it became voluntary.
And so I was in President Rutter's office one day, and Fred was working at the 40 Acres Club.
And he says, I see Fred has gone to the University of Texas.
Why didn't he go to A&M?
Well, I had to explain it to him, more or less like an excuse.
I always said, well, I'm glad I had tenure anyway.
Yeah.
Did, as you recall your classes, do you remember any kinds of unusual events over a woman being in class or a black student being in class?
Well, of course, we co-educated and black at the same time.
But we had a number of wives of students.
And this yell leader was in this class.
And she was in there.
And he was very nasty about her and all that stuff.
She kind of straightened him out.
But this is back.
Here's a purebred Aggie that just resented it badly.
But in general, I don't know of anything particular about it.
If we had had a faculty referendum on, the whole faculty, on co-education, non-compulsory core, racial integration, higher admission requirements, what do you think the vote would have been?
Back in those days?
Which one would they prefer?
No, no, no.
Would they have voted for any of those, all of those?
I don't know that they would.
Let's see.
I believe that the average faculty member would have voted for most of those, if not all.
And Mr. Rutter said to me privately, he said, I didn't need a faculty referendum because I assumed the faculty favored all of those.
Do you remember any racial events?
The only one I remember is a
a young black fellow who was on active duty and was sent here as an undergraduate student.
And I advised him and so forth.
And then I discovered he had been transferred out to New Mexico or someplace.
And so I asked why he left.
And he said, well, he was married to a white woman.
And they just, you know, pressure on me.
This is the only occurrence I remember.
We really didn't have hardly any blacks in there, but the ones we had, I remember, did okay.
Now, as women began to major in engineering, did they handle the work academically as well as the men did?
The what?
Were their grades as high?
The women?
Oh, I loved them.
I think it was much better.
And I think they were very comparable.
I can't distinguish at all whether they did any worse or better or this sort of thing.
In all of your years as a faculty member, can you share any anecdotes about any pranks or teasings or good bull that students ever attempted on you or any other faculty member?
No, I can't really.
No students played any trick on you?
No tricks.
What was your nickname?
I didn't have one.
I can't remember that I did.
I never heard of one.
They were abandoned, I think, by the time I started teaching.
For one thing, the students were so scattered.
It wasn't like when we were
eating and living and going to class together that we all more or less got nicknames.
So that just has played out.
Now, you all moved from Bolton Hall to what?
To Zachary when it opened.
We've been there ever since it opened.
What was it like?
Describe that change.
Well, of course, I was kind of in charge of working with Nash, the architect, and also the equipment we had and the,
the people furnishing equipment and this sort of thing.
And so I was involved in those details.
And also when the faculty member had some kind of a question, they were supposed to come through me and I would try to get an answer from Nash or what else it was.
So.
Did, was that architect and his staff, were they sensitive to the suggestions that you made?
Oh, I think so, yeah.
I didn't hear much.
One was worried about getting his equipment up to the floor.
He didn't think the elevator was big enough.
So I went over and measured it, and it had a back door, too.
So it worked out all right.
He was really worried about getting his equipment up there.
Now, let's see.
Dan Benson was dean in those days, right?
Oh, yeah.
Describe him.
Make believe that I had never met him.
Describe him in personality and style.
Fred Benson?
Well, of course, I've known him all along while he was dean.
I even went to talk to him about a job, and he referred me to the department and so forth.
But he certainly was a strong dean.
There was one man that he got rid of.
The students complained to me about the fact that he was downgrading the school and all that sort of thing.
And so I said, well, you've got to go talk to the dean about him and let him know.
And what Benson did was give him, supervised his research and so forth, and found he was really liking it.
And this is the way he was able to get rid of him, which is pretty hard to do in a tenured faculty.
But I thought he ran a tall ship and had good administrators with him and everything.
Did he earn the trust of the faculty?
Oh, I think very much so.
Mm-hmm.
Oh, Page now, he didn't do such a good job, I don't think.
I'm not sure why.
I was not up in that area where they knew about that.
I was thinking the other day, there ought to be some
engineering facility on this campus named in honor of Fred Benson.
He earned that, I think.
Well, let's see.
Let's try to kind of draw this near an end.
What has it meant to you in your life that you went to Texas A&M as a student?
As a student?
What did your coming here, instead of going somewhere else,
What has been, what is the meaning of it?
Well, I have no doubt I came to the right place.
I feel like the relationships that I developed with my fellow students and the faculty and the more or less focus that we had on an education and of course the athletics is a part of it, but
I just feel like out of 52 in the class of 45 that left here in orders, 52 of them, all in the Signal Corps, and they said report to Camp Beauregard at your own expense.
And they didn't get to finish until after the war.
And after 50 years, I got 27 of them to come back.
Some of them had not come back after the war, but they came back anyway.
So I think this type of loyalty you have, I think the university is unique.
And also, I feel like it has endured pretty well.
And I feel like they're still Aggies, they still want to come here, and they have developed the esprit de corps that we had not as much, of course,
The classes are too big and too scattered, but it's just a unique school.
What contributes to that spirit?
Well, they start out with freshman week.
Of course, they got that summer, and the freshman week is so important, I think.
And, of course, they have so many things like the L practice and the student bodies sitting together and this sort of thing.
Really, it's interesting that it still persists.

I know I talked to the woman in the Memorial Student Center in the bookstore, and she had lived in Austin, and then she was over here, and she just noticed it, how it was so different from over at the university.
I've had a theory that
these events you mentioned, including Silver Taps and Luster and Midnight Y'all Practice and all of those, that they are inclusive.
Male, female, core, civilian, short, tall, rich, poor, country or town.
If you're one of us, come on and join.
And then the grand finale is commencement, where every name is called, every hand is taken, that it is inclusive instead of being exclusive.
and that that really helps.
And that causes me to ask, did you not, when you were a student or since then, were you aware of any secret fraternities?
Yes.
So secret, the only indication I had of this apparently is when they decided to boycott the Bryan Theaters.
Apparently it came from that, but it really... Do you know what the names of the groups were?
No, I never knew.
It's so insignificant, that's the only case I've ever heard of that.
What little I can find, apparently the primary purpose of the one or more secret fraternities was to get their own members in key positions
student leadership position.
Really?
To get one of their own to be the corps commander, the head yell leader and so forth.
But that was secret.
Let's see.
We've already talked about the key ingredients of being an Aggie and so forth.
Oh, the Aggie ring.
Was there any kind of ritual in those days of what you did when you got it?
No, I don't remember any.
But, of course, different outfits would have different rituals, I guess.
All right.
Three other things to mention.
One of them.
If you have any papers, any stuff you have saved,
that you ever wanted to part with, I beg you, please give it to the A&M Archives in the Cushing Library.
If this is any letters, any memorabilia, any notes, any photographs that you want to part with, that's the place where it would be preserved.
Okay, next one.
Let's make believe that somebody walks up to you and gives you a million dollar check with only one requirement.

you must give it to texas a m but you decide what would be done with it if you were to give a million dollars to a m what would you want it to be used for what good what good part of a m would be most important to you well it has to be the faculty i think i can't i don't know it really
I thought about it.
It's disturbing about the core.
If you notice that graph that was in the newspaper this week, well, you see what's going to happen.
I mean, it's really because you've only got 400 or 500 in the freshman and sophomore class, and I don't see how you're going to, I feel like the core's kind of archaic.
And almost every one of those freshmen has a scholarship.
I will add, that's what they've got to do, of course, to get them.
And so many of them are dropping out after the first two years now.
After two years?
Well, that's okay.
I think it's fine what they're doing.
It's a good image for the thing, but I'm afraid the people at a distance that see the football games think this is what we are.
Oh, yes.
Mm-hmm.
Okay, last question.
What feelings do you hold in your heart for Texas A&M now?
Now?
Well, I'm very fond of my whole experience.
Not as much as anything living here.
And seeing old Aggies coming back when they retire, moving here, and...
It's just so unique because, of course, my wife taught for 32 years.
Always students show up of hers.
I don't see hardly any of mine because they're all scattered.
But I don't know.
What was your question again?
What feelings do you have for Texas A&M in your heart?
Just a great fondness for it, of course.
That's the best thing I can say.
There's not a single thing about my life that I would want to do differently.
That's what I've done.
